##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.AzapiDiagnosticSettings.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { AzapiDiagnosticSettings } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

AzapiDiagnosticSettings.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.AzapiDiagnosticSettings.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

### AzapiResource <a name="AzapiResource" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.AzapiResource"></a>

Abstract base class for version-aware Azure resource management.

AzapiResource provides a unified framework for creating Azure resources
with automatic version management, schema validation, property transformation,
and migration analysis. It extends the existing AzapiResource class while
maintaining full backward compatibility.

This class implements the core framework that enables:
- Automatic resolution of the latest API version when none is specified
- Explicit version pinning for environments requiring stability
- Schema-driven property validation and transformation
- Migration analysis with breaking change detection
- Deprecation warnings and upgrade recommendations

Subclasses must implement the abstract methods to provide resource-specific
configuration while the framework handles all version management complexity.

*Example*

```typescript
Usage with explicit version pinning:
new MyResource(this, "resource", {
name: "my-resource",
location: "eastus",
apiVersion: "2024-01-01" // Pin to specific version
});
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.testing.BaseTestStack.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { testing } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

testing.BaseTestStack.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.testing.BaseTestStack.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.DataAzapiClientConfig.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { core_azure } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

core_azure.DataAzapiClientConfig.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.DataAzapiClientConfig.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.DataAzapiResource.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { DataAzapiResource } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

DataAzapiResource.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.DataAzapiResource.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.DataAzapiResource.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { core_azure } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

core_azure.DataAzapiResource.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.DataAzapiResource.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.Resource.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { Resource } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

Resource.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.Resource.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.Resource.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { core_azure } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

core_azure.Resource.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.Resource.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

---

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ResourceAction.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { ResourceAction } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

ResourceAction.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ResourceAction.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

---

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.ResourceAction.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { core_azure } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

core_azure.ResourceAction.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.ResourceAction.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

---

### ResourceGroup <a name="ResourceGroup" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ResourceGroup"></a>

Unified Azure Resource Group implementation.

This class provides a single, version-aware implementation that replaces all
version-specific Resource Group classes. It automatically handles version
resolution, schema validation, and property transformation while maintaining
full backward compatibility.

The class uses the VersionedAzapiResource framework to provide:
- Automatic latest version resolution (2025-03-01 as of this implementation)
- Support for explicit version pinning when stability is required
- Schema-driven property validation and transformation
- Migration analysis and deprecation warnings
- Full JSII compliance for multi-language support

*Example*

```typescript
// Usage with explicit version pinning:
const resourceGroup = new ResourceGroup(this, "rg", {
  name: "my-resource-group",
  location: "eastus",
  apiVersion: "2024-11-01", // Pin to specific version
  tags: { environment: "production" }
});
```

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ResourceGroup.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { ResourceGroup } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

ResourceGroup.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ResourceGroup.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

### ResourceGroup <a name="ResourceGroup" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.azure_resourcegroup.ResourceGroup"></a>

Unified Azure Resource Group implementation.

This class provides a single, version-aware implementation that replaces all
version-specific Resource Group classes. It automatically handles version
resolution, schema validation, and property transformation while maintaining
full backward compatibility.

The class uses the VersionedAzapiResource framework to provide:
- Automatic latest version resolution (2025-03-01 as of this implementation)
- Support for explicit version pinning when stability is required
- Schema-driven property validation and transformation
- Migration analysis and deprecation warnings
- Full JSII compliance for multi-language support

*Example*

```typescript
// Usage with explicit version pinning:
const resourceGroup = new ResourceGroup(this, "rg", {
  name: "my-resource-group",
  location: "eastus",
  apiVersion: "2024-11-01", // Pin to specific version
  tags: { environment: "production" }
});
```

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.azure_resourcegroup.ResourceGroup.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { azure_resourcegroup } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

azure_resourcegroup.ResourceGroup.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.azure_resourcegroup.ResourceGroup.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

### StorageAccount <a name="StorageAccount" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.StorageAccount"></a>

Unified Azure Storage Account implementation.

This class provides a single, version-aware implementation that replaces all
version-specific Storage Account classes. It automatically handles version
resolution, schema validation, and property transformation while maintaining
full backward compatibility.

*Example*

```typescript
// Usage with explicit version pinning:
const storageAccount = new StorageAccount(this, "storage", {
  name: "mystorageaccount",
  location: "eastus",
  resourceGroupId: resourceGroup.id,
  sku: { name: "Standard_LRS" },
  apiVersion: "2023-05-01",
});
```

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.StorageAccount.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { StorageAccount } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

StorageAccount.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.StorageAccount.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.azure_storageaccount.StorageAccount.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { azure_storageaccount } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

azure_storageaccount.StorageAccount.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.azure_storageaccount.StorageAccount.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.UpdateResource.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { UpdateResource } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

UpdateResource.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.UpdateResource.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

---

##### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.UpdateResource.isConstruct"></a>

```typescript
import { core_azure } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

core_azure.UpdateResource.isConstruct(x: any)
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.UpdateResource.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- *Type:* any

Any object.

---

The ID of the azure resource in which this resource is created.

It supports different kinds of deployment scope for **top level** resources:

- resource group scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of a resource group, it's recommended to manage a resource group by azurerm_resource_group.
- management group scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of a management group, it's recommended to manage a management group by azurerm_management_group.
- extension scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of the resource you're adding the extension to.
- subscription scope: `parent_id` should be like \x60/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000\x60
- tenant scope: `parent_id` should be /

For child level resources, the `parent_id` should be the ID of its parent resource, for example, subnet resource's `parent_id` is the ID of the vnet.

For type `Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups`, the `parent_id` could be omitted, it defaults to subscription ID specified in provider or the default subscription (You could check the default subscription by azure cli command: `az account show`).

The attribute can accept either a list or a map.

**List**: A list of paths that need to be exported from the response body. Setting it to `["*"]` will export the full response body. Here's an example. If it sets to `["properties.loginServer", "properties.policies.quarantinePolicy.status"]`, it will set the following HCL object to the computed property output.

```text
{
properties = {
loginServer = "registry1.azurecr.io"
policies = {
quarantinePolicy = {
	status = "disabled"
}
}
}
}
```

- **Map**: A map where the key is the name for the result and the value is a JMESPath query string to filter the response. Here's an example. If it sets to `{"login_server": "properties.loginServer", "quarantine_status": "properties.policies.quarantinePolicy.status"}`, it will set the following HCL object to the computed property output.

```text
{
"login_server" = "registry1.azurecr.io"
"quarantine_status" = "disabled"
}
```

To learn more about JMESPath, visit [JMESPath](https://jmespath.org/).

##### `parentId`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="parentId" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.DataAzapiResourceConfig.property.parentId"></a>

```typescript
public readonly parentId: string;
```

- *Type:* string

The ID of the azure resource in which this resource is created.

It supports different kinds of deployment scope for **top level** resources:

- resource group scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of a resource group, it's recommended to manage a resource group by azurerm_resource_group.
- management group scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of a management group, it's recommended to manage a management group by azurerm_management_group.
- extension scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of the resource you're adding the extension to.
- subscription scope: `parent_id` should be like \x60/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000\x60
- tenant scope: `parent_id` should be /

For child level resources, the `parent_id` should be the ID of its parent resource, for example, subnet resource's `parent_id` is the ID of the vnet.

For type `Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups`, the `parent_id` could be omitted, it defaults to subscription ID specified in provider or the default subscription (You could check the default subscription by azure cli command: `az account show`).

Docs at Terraform Registry: {@link https://registry.terraform.io/providers/azure/azapi/2.7.0/docs/data-sources/resource#parent_id DataAzapiResource#parent_id}

##### `responseExportValues`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="responseExportValues" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.DataAzapiResourceConfig.property.responseExportValues"></a>

```typescript
public readonly responseExportValues: {[ key: string ]: any};
```

- *Type:* {[ key: string ]: any}

The attribute can accept either a list or a map.

**List**: A list of paths that need to be exported from the response body. Setting it to `["*"]` will export the full response body. Here's an example. If it sets to `["properties.loginServer", "properties.policies.quarantinePolicy.status"]`, it will set the following HCL object to the computed property output.

```text
{
properties = {
loginServer = "registry1.azurecr.io"
policies = {
quarantinePolicy = {
	status = "disabled"
}
}
}
}
```

- **Map**: A map where the key is the name for the result and the value is a JMESPath query string to filter the response. Here's an example. If it sets to `{"login_server": "properties.loginServer", "quarantine_status": "properties.policies.quarantinePolicy.status"}`, it will set the following HCL object to the computed property output.

```text
{
"login_server" = "registry1.azurecr.io"
"quarantine_status" = "disabled"
}
```

To learn more about JMESPath, visit [JMESPath](https://jmespath.org/).


Docs at Terraform Registry: {@link https://registry.terraform.io/providers/azure/azapi/2.7.0/docs/data-sources/resource#response_export_values DataAzapiResource#response_export_values}

##### `parentId`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="parentId" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ResourceConfig.property.parentId"></a>

```typescript
public readonly parentId: string;
```

- *Type:* string

The ID of the azure resource in which this resource is created.

It supports different kinds of deployment scope for **top level** resources:

- resource group scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of a resource group, it's recommended to manage a resource group by azurerm_resource_group.
- management group scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of a management group, it's recommended to manage a management group by azurerm_management_group.
- extension scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of the resource you're adding the extension to.
- subscription scope: `parent_id` should be like \x60/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000\x60
- tenant scope: `parent_id` should be /

For child level resources, the `parent_id` should be the ID of its parent resource, for example, subnet resource's `parent_id` is the ID of the vnet.

For type `Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups`, the `parent_id` could be omitted, it defaults to subscription ID specified in provider or the default subscription (You could check the default subscription by azure cli command: `az account show`).

Docs at Terraform Registry: {@link https://registry.terraform.io/providers/azure/azapi/2.7.0/docs/resources/resource#parent_id Resource#parent_id}

##### `replaceTriggersExternalValues`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="replaceTriggersExternalValues" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ResourceConfig.property.replaceTriggersExternalValues"></a>

```typescript
public readonly replaceTriggersExternalValues: {[ key: string ]: any};
```

- *Type:* {[ key: string ]: any}

Will trigger a replace of the resource when the value changes and is not `null`.

This can be used by practitioners to force a replace of the resource when certain values change, e.g. changing the SKU of a virtual machine based on the value of variables or locals. The value is a `dynamic`, so practitioners can compose the input however they wish. For a "break glass" set the value to `null` to prevent the plan modifier taking effect.
If you have `null` values that you do want to be tracked as affecting the resource replacement, include these inside an object.
Advanced use cases are possible and resource replacement can be triggered by values external to the resource, for example when a dependent resource changes.

e.g. to replace a resource when either the SKU or os_type attributes change:

```hcl
resource "azapi_resource" "example" {
name      = var.name
type      = "Microsoft.Network/publicIPAddresses@2023-11-01"
parent_id = "/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/example"
body = {
properties = {
  sku   = var.sku
  zones = var.zones
}
}

replace_triggers_external_values = [
var.sku,
var.zones,
]
}
```


Docs at Terraform Registry: {@link https://registry.terraform.io/providers/azure/azapi/2.7.0/docs/resources/resource#replace_triggers_external_values Resource#replace_triggers_external_values}

##### `responseExportValues`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="responseExportValues" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ResourceConfig.property.responseExportValues"></a>

```typescript
public readonly responseExportValues: {[ key: string ]: any};
```

- *Type:* {[ key: string ]: any}

The attribute can accept either a list or a map.

**List**: A list of paths that need to be exported from the response body. Setting it to `["*"]` will export the full response body. Here's an example. If it sets to `["properties.loginServer", "properties.policies.quarantinePolicy.status"]`, it will set the following HCL object to the computed property output.

```text
{
properties = {
loginServer = "registry1.azurecr.io"
policies = {
quarantinePolicy = {
	status = "disabled"
}
}
}
}
```

- **Map**: A map where the key is the name for the result and the value is a JMESPath query string to filter the response. Here's an example. If it sets to `{"login_server": "properties.loginServer", "quarantine_status": "properties.policies.quarantinePolicy.status"}`, it will set the following HCL object to the computed property output.

```text
{
"login_server" = "registry1.azurecr.io"
"quarantine_status" = "disabled"
}
```

To learn more about JMESPath, visit [JMESPath](https://jmespath.org/).


Docs at Terraform Registry: {@link https://registry.terraform.io/providers/azure/azapi/2.7.0/docs/resources/resource#response_export_values Resource#response_export_values}

##### `parentId`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="parentId" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.ResourceConfig.property.parentId"></a>

```typescript
public readonly parentId: string;
```

- *Type:* string

The ID of the azure resource in which this resource is created.

It supports different kinds of deployment scope for **top level** resources:

- resource group scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of a resource group, it's recommended to manage a resource group by azurerm_resource_group.
- management group scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of a management group, it's recommended to manage a management group by azurerm_management_group.
- extension scope: `parent_id` should be the ID of the resource you're adding the extension to.
- subscription scope: `parent_id` should be like \x60/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000\x60
- tenant scope: `parent_id` should be /

For child level resources, the `parent_id` should be the ID of its parent resource, for example, subnet resource's `parent_id` is the ID of the vnet.

For type `Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups`, the `parent_id` could be omitted, it defaults to subscription ID specified in provider or the default subscription (You could check the default subscription by azure cli command: `az account show`).

Docs at Terraform Registry: {@link https://registry.terraform.io/providers/azure/azapi/2.7.0/docs/resources/resource#parent_id Resource#parent_id}

##### `replaceTriggersExternalValues`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="replaceTriggersExternalValues" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.ResourceConfig.property.replaceTriggersExternalValues"></a>

```typescript
public readonly replaceTriggersExternalValues: {[ key: string ]: any};
```

- *Type:* {[ key: string ]: any}

Will trigger a replace of the resource when the value changes and is not `null`.

This can be used by practitioners to force a replace of the resource when certain values change, e.g. changing the SKU of a virtual machine based on the value of variables or locals. The value is a `dynamic`, so practitioners can compose the input however they wish. For a "break glass" set the value to `null` to prevent the plan modifier taking effect.
If you have `null` values that you do want to be tracked as affecting the resource replacement, include these inside an object.
Advanced use cases are possible and resource replacement can be triggered by values external to the resource, for example when a dependent resource changes.

e.g. to replace a resource when either the SKU or os_type attributes change:

```hcl
resource "azapi_resource" "example" {
name      = var.name
type      = "Microsoft.Network/publicIPAddresses@2023-11-01"
parent_id = "/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/example"
body = {
properties = {
  sku   = var.sku
  zones = var.zones
}
}

replace_triggers_external_values = [
var.sku,
var.zones,
]
}
```


Docs at Terraform Registry: {@link https://registry.terraform.io/providers/azure/azapi/2.7.0/docs/resources/resource#replace_triggers_external_values Resource#replace_triggers_external_values}

---

##### `responseExportValues`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="responseExportValues" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.ResourceConfig.property.responseExportValues"></a>

```typescript
public readonly responseExportValues: {[ key: string ]: any};
```

- *Type:* {[ key: string ]: any}

The attribute can accept either a list or a map.

**List**: A list of paths that need to be exported from the response body. Setting it to `["*"]` will export the full response body. Here's an example. If it sets to `["properties.loginServer", "properties.policies.quarantinePolicy.status"]`, it will set the following HCL object to the computed property output.

```text
{
properties = {
loginServer = "registry1.azurecr.io"
policies = {
quarantinePolicy = {
	status = "disabled"
}
}
}
}
```

- **Map**: A map where the key is the name for the result and the value is a JMESPath query string to filter the response. Here's an example. If it sets to `{"login_server": "properties.loginServer", "quarantine_status": "properties.policies.quarantinePolicy.status"}`, it will set the following HCL object to the computed property output.

```text
{
"login_server" = "registry1.azurecr.io"
"quarantine_status" = "disabled"
}
```

To learn more about JMESPath, visit [JMESPath](https://jmespath.org/).


Docs at Terraform Registry: {@link https://registry.terraform.io/providers/azure/azapi/2.7.0/docs/resources/resource#response_export_values Resource#response_export_values}

## Classes <a name="Classes" id="Classes"></a>

### ApiVersionManager <a name="ApiVersionManager" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager"></a>

ApiVersionManager singleton class for centralized version management.

This class manages API versions for Azure resources, providing version resolution,
compatibility analysis, and migration guidance. It implements a JSII-compliant
singleton pattern for thread-safe operations across multiple language bindings.

Key Features:
- Thread-safe singleton implementation
- Version registry management with full lifecycle support
- Advanced version resolution with constraint-based selection
- Comprehensive migration analysis with effort estimation
- Extensive validation and error handling

*Example*

```typescript
const manager = ApiVersionManager.getInstance();
manager.registerResourceType('Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups', versions);
const latest = manager.getLatestVersion('Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups');
const analysis = manager.analyzeMigration('Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups', '2024-01-01', '2024-11-01');
```

| --- | --- |
| <code><a href="#@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.analyzeMigration">analyzeMigration</a></code> | Analyzes migration requirements between two versions. |
| <code><a href="#@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.latestVersion">latestVersion</a></code> | Gets the latest active version for a resource type. |
| <code><a href="#@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.registeredResourceTypes">registeredResourceTypes</a></code> | Gets all registered resource types. |
| <code><a href="#@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.registerResourceType">registerResourceType</a></code> | Registers a resource type with its version configurations. |
| <code><a href="#@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.supportedVersions">supportedVersions</a></code> | Gets all supported versions for a resource type. |

| <code><a href="#@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.versionConfig">versionConfig</a></code> | Gets the configuration for a specific version of a resource type. |
| <code><a href="#@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.versionLifecycle">versionLifecycle</a></code> | Gets version lifecycle information for a specific version. |

---

##### `analyzeMigration` <a name="analyzeMigration" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.analyzeMigration"></a>

```typescript
public analyzeMigration(resourceType: string, fromVersion: string, toVersion: string): MigrationAnalysis
```

Analyzes migration requirements between two versions.

Performs comprehensive analysis of the migration path between source and
target versions, including compatibility assessment, breaking changes
identification, effort estimation, and upgrade feasibility.

*Example*

```typescript
const analysis = manager.analyzeMigration(
  'Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups',
  '2024-01-01',
  '2024-11-01'
);

console.log(`Compatible: ${analysis.compatible}`);
console.log(`Effort: ${analysis.estimatedEffort}`);
console.log(`Breaking changes: ${analysis.breakingChanges.length}`);
```


###### `resourceType`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="resourceType" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.analyzeMigration.parameter.resourceType"></a>

- *Type:* string

The Azure resource type.

---

- *Type:* string

The source version to migrate from.

---

###### `toVersion`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="toVersion" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.analyzeMigration.parameter.toVersion"></a>

- *Type:* string

The target version to migrate to.

---

##### `latestVersion` <a name="latestVersion" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.latestVersion"></a>

```typescript
public latestVersion(resourceType: string): string
```

Gets the latest active version for a resource type.

Returns the most recent version with ACTIVE support level. If no active
versions are found, returns the most recent version regardless of support level.

*Example*

```typescript
const latest = manager.latestVersion('Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups');
// Returns: "2024-11-01"
```


###### `resourceType`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="resourceType" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.latestVersion.parameter.resourceType"></a>

- *Type:* string

The Azure resource type to get the latest version for.

---

##### `registeredResourceTypes` <a name="registeredResourceTypes" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.registeredResourceTypes"></a>

```typescript
public registeredResourceTypes(): string[]
```

Gets all registered resource types.

Returns an array of all Azure resource types that have been registered
with the version manager.

*Example*

```typescript
const resourceTypes = manager.registeredResourceTypes();
// Returns: ["Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups", "Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts", ...]
```


##### `registerResourceType` <a name="registerResourceType" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.ApiVersionManager.registerResourceType"></a>

```typescript
public registerResourceType(resourceType: string, versions: VersionConfig[]): void
```

Registers a resource type with its version configurations.

This method stores version metadata for a specific Azure resource type,
including schemas, lifecycle information, and migration data. It validates
the input and maintains internal indexes for efficient lookups.

*Example*

```typescript
manager.registerResourceType('Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups', [
  {
    version: '2024-01-01',
    schema: { resourceType: 'Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups', version: '2024-01-01', properties: {}, required: [] },
    supportLevel: VersionSupportLevel.ACTIVE,
    releaseDate: '2024-01-01'
  }
]);
```

### SchemaMapper <a name="SchemaMapper" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper"></a>

SchemaMapper class for property transformation and validation.

This class provides a comprehensive property transformation engine that enables
mapping between different API schema versions with full validation support.
It implements JSII-compliant patterns for multi-language code generation.

The SchemaMapper handles:
- Property transformation between schema versions
- Validation against API schema definitions
- Default value injection for new properties
- Nested object and array processing
- Detailed error reporting with property paths

*Example*

```typescript
const schema: ApiSchema = {
  resourceType: 'Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups',
  version: '2024-11-01',
  properties: {
    name: { dataType: PropertyType.STRING, required: true },
    location: { dataType: PropertyType.STRING, required: true }
  },
  required: ['name', 'location']
};

const mapper = SchemaMapper.create(schema);
const result = mapper.validateProperties({ name: 'myRG', location: 'eastus' });
```

| **Name** | **Description** |
| --- | --- |
| <code><a href="#@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper.applyDefaults">applyDefaults</a></code> | Applies default values to properties based on schema definitions. |
| <code><a href="#@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper.mapProperty">mapProperty</a></code> | Maps a single property value using transformation rules. |
| <code><a href="#@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper.transformProperties">transformProperties</a></code> | Transforms properties from source format to target schema format. |
| <code><a href="#@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper.validateProperties">validateProperties</a></code> | Validates properties against the schema definition. |

##### `applyDefaults` <a name="applyDefaults" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper.applyDefaults"></a>

```typescript
public applyDefaults(properties: any): any
```

Applies default values to properties based on schema definitions.

This method injects default values for properties that are not provided
but have default values defined in the schema. It preserves existing
property values and only adds defaults for missing properties.

*Example*

```typescript
const props = { name: 'myRG' };
const withDefaults = mapper.applyDefaults(props);
// If schema defines location default as 'eastus':
// Result: { name: 'myRG', location: 'eastus' }
```


###### `properties`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="properties" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper.applyDefaults.parameter.properties"></a>

- *Type:* any

The properties to apply defaults to.


Maps a single property value using transformation rules.

This method applies transformation logic to a single property value based on

and custom transformations.

*Example*

```typescript
const targetProp = { dataType: PropertyType.STRING, required: true };
const mapped = mapper.mapProperty('name', 'myResourceGroup', targetProp);
```

##### `transformProperties` <a name="transformProperties" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper.transformProperties"></a>

```typescript
public transformProperties(sourceProps: any, targetSchema: ApiSchema): any
```

Transforms properties from source format to target schema format.

This method applies transformation rules to convert properties from one schema
format to another. It handles property renaming, restructuring, type conversion,
and nested object/array transformations based on the target schema definition.

*Example*

```typescript
const sourceProps = { oldName: 'value', location: 'eastus' };
const targetSchema = {
  transformationRules: { oldName: 'newName' },
  properties: { newName: { dataType: PropertyType.STRING } }
};
const transformed = mapper.transformProperties(sourceProps, targetSchema);
// Result: { newName: 'value', location: 'eastus' }
```


###### `sourceProps`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="sourceProps" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper.transformProperties.parameter.sourceProps"></a>

- *Type:* any

The source properties to transform.

---

###### `targetSchema`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="targetSchema" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper.transformProperties.parameter.targetSchema"></a>

- *Type:* @microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.ApiSchema

The target schema to transform properties to.

---

##### `validateProperties` <a name="validateProperties" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper.validateProperties"></a>

```typescript
public validateProperties(properties: any): ValidationResult
```

Validates properties against the schema definition.

This method performs comprehensive validation of properties against the
configured schema. It checks required properties, data types, validation rules,
and provides detailed error reporting with property path information.

*Example*

```typescript
const properties = { name: 'myRG', location: 'eastus', tags: { env: 'dev' } };
const result = mapper.validateProperties(properties);

if (!result.valid) {
  console.log('Validation errors:', result.errors);
  console.log('Property errors:', result.propertyErrors);
}
```


###### `properties`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="properties" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.SchemaMapper.validateProperties.parameter.properties"></a>

- *Type:* any

The properties to validate.

##### `transformProperties` <a name="transformProperties" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.SchemaMapper.transformProperties"></a>

```typescript
public transformProperties(sourceProps: any, targetSchema: ApiSchema): any
```

Transforms properties from source format to target schema format.

This method applies transformation rules to convert properties from one schema
format to another. It handles property renaming, restructuring, type conversion,
and nested object/array transformations based on the target schema definition.

*Example*

```typescript
const sourceProps = { oldName: 'value', location: 'eastus' };
const targetSchema = {
  transformationRules: { oldName: 'newName' },
  properties: { newName: { dataType: PropertyType.STRING } }
};
const transformed = mapper.transformProperties(sourceProps, targetSchema);
// Result: { newName: 'value', location: 'eastus' }
```

- *Type:* @microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.ApiSchema

The target schema to transform properties to.

---

##### `validateProperties` <a name="validateProperties" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.SchemaMapper.validateProperties"></a>

```typescript
public validateProperties(properties: any): ValidationResult
```

Validates properties against the schema definition.

This method performs comprehensive validation of properties against the
configured schema. It checks required properties, data types, validation rules,
and provides detailed error reporting with property path information.

*Example*

```typescript
const properties = { name: 'myRG', location: 'eastus', tags: { env: 'dev' } };
const result = mapper.validateProperties(properties);

if (!result.valid) {
  console.log('Validation errors:', result.errors);
  console.log('Property errors:', result.propertyErrors);
}
```


###### `properties`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="properties" id="@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs.core_azure.SchemaMapper.validateProperties.parameter.properties"></a>

```typescript
import { core_azure } from '@microsoft/terraform-cdk-constructs'

core_azure.SchemaMapper.create(schema: ApiSchema)
```

Creates a new SchemaMapper instance for the specified schema.

This factory method creates a SchemaMapper configured for a specific API schema.
The schema defines the structure, validation rules, and transformation mappings
that will be used for property operations.

*Example*

```typescript
const schema: ApiSchema = {
  resourceType: 'Microsoft.Resources/resourceGroups',
  version: '2024-11-01',
  properties: { name: { dataType: PropertyType.STRING, required: true } },
  required: ['name']
};
const mapper = SchemaMapper.create(schema);
```
